This paper is about developing methods for speech processing in the absence of transcriptions, lexicons, or language modelling text, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Specifically, the paper focuses on unsupervised speech recognition, which involves clustering and segmenting audio into word-like units. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CL (Computation and Language), which includes research on NLP and speech processing. 

The paper also uses Bayesian modelling and machine learning techniques, which are common in sub-categories such as cs.SD (Sound), cs.SI (Speech Recognition), and cs.LG (Machine Learning). Finally, the paper discusses the use of autoencoder-like feature extractors, which is a technique commonly used in cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) for unsupervised learning.
